# OMBI — Open Metaverse Browser Initiative

> **This file is the project's shared knowledge base.** Any developer or AI assistant who clones this repository inherits this file as their starting context. It is not a sequential log — it does not record session history or append dated entries. It describes what the project *is right now*: architecture, codebase structure, dependencies, build decisions and their rationale, conventions, and roadmap status. Update sections in place as the project evolves. Session-level notes belong in session log files, not here.

## Overview

**OMBI** (Open Metaverse Browser Initiative) is an organizational unit under the Metaverse Standards Forum. Its mission is to define and build a reference implementation of the Open Metaverse Browser (OMB).

The project produces two components:

- **Sneeze** — the Metaverse Browser Engine (MBE). A standalone, reusable engine library (static `.lib`). Analogous to Blink in the web browser world. Owns all third-party dependencies (Wasmtime, SPIRV-Tools, OpenXR, curl, RmlUi, ANARI, nlohmann/json, Halogen) and the engine modules that wrap them (`wasm/`, `spirv/`, `xr/`, `net/`, `ui/`, `core/`, and future `som/`, `smap/`, `compute/`, `identity/`, `audio/`). All test executables (WasmTest, SpvTest, XrTest, NetTest, UiTest) belong to Sneeze. Another team could build a different metaverse browser on top of Sneeze without touching Artemis.

- **Artemis** — the metaverse browser application. The single `.exe`. Analogous to Chrome/Chromium. A thin application layer that consumes Sneeze: window management (`canvas/`), user chrome, and `main()`. Owns SDL3 (windowing/input is application-level, not engine-level). The disposable solar system demo (`astro/`) also belongs here. Artemis is **not open source** — proprietary copyright headers.

**Rubidium** was the original working name for the combined browser before the split into Sneeze + Artemis was decided. The codebase has been renamed — all namespaces, include guards, string literals, and source references now use `sneeze`. **The split has been executed.** Sneeze is a static `.lib`; Artemis is a separate repo (sibling directory) that compiles Sneeze inline via `add_subdirectory`.

**Dependency ownership:** Sneeze declares and owns all third-party engine dependencies. Artemis depends on Sneeze and SDL3. When Artemis links against Sneeze, CMake transitively pulls in all of Sneeze's dependencies via PUBLIC declarations. SDL3 belongs to Artemis, not Sneeze — the engine is embeddable without owning windowing.

