## Architecture Reference

The OMB architecture is fully documented in `OMB_Architecture_4.md` (the authoritative architecture document, version 4, 2026 Q2, maintained outside this repo). This document covers the MBE (Metaverse Browser Engine), its core abstractions, the SOM, rendering engine, UI toolkit, identity, avatars, spatial audio, and the content provider ecosystem.

### MBE Core Abstractions

The MBE relies on six industry-adopted open standards that abstract the underlying hardware. These are genuinely different kinds of things — APIs, bytecode formats, and a programming model — which is why they are called "core abstractions" rather than "runtime interfaces."

- **ANARI** — rendering abstraction (scene description, not GPU calls). High-level scene graph API where the browser describes *what* to render and the ANARI device decides *how*. Extremely thin — imposes no measurable overhead.
- **SPIR-V Compute via ANARI** — browser-internal GPU compute. Parallel workloads (physics, spatial audio, proximity, coordinate transforms, IK) are authored as GLSL compute shaders, compiled to SPIR-V at build time, and dispatched through ANARI at runtime. ANARI abstracts the underlying GPU API (Vulkan, Metal, DX12) — the browser never interacts with GPU compute APIs directly. Not visible to services — it's the browser team's internal compute tool.
- **SPIR-V** — GPU interchange format for both graphics shaders and compute shaders. Content providers ship SPIR-V bytecode; the browser validates it (SPIRV-Tools) and passes it to ANARI, which handles backend translation internally.
- **OpenXR** — device I/O abstraction for VR/AR headsets, controllers, hand tracking, eye tracking. Confirmed indispensable — no realistic alternative exists.
- **WASM** — sandboxed execution for third-party service logic. Each connected service runs WASM modules with isolated memory, CPU budgets, and controlled host access. A misbehaving module cannot crash the browser, read other services' data, or access the filesystem.
- **SMAP** (Service Model Access Protocol) — fabric connectivity and service driver layer. Abstracts the network so the browser can connect to any spatial fabric without knowledge of its underlying protocol.

### Core Concepts
- **Spatial Fabric** — a collection of services that together define a spatial environment
- **Service** — a discrete unit of functionality within a spatial fabric
- **SOM** (Scene Object Model) — the browser's internal scene graph (like the DOM for 3D)
- **Proximity** — the primary discovery and connection mechanism, replacing URLs

